Adult. Coloration: Summer form: General colour green to yellow. Concave area around discal foveae of vertex slightly darker. Ocelli orange. Compound eyes grey. Antenna light yellow, apices of segments IV–VIII brown, segments IX–X entirely black. Thoracic terga with orange stripes. Legs yellow. Fore wing transparent and more or less yellowish (
Fig. 28
), veins yellow, without marking near apex of claval suture. Male and female terminalia yellow.

Structure: Summer form: Body glabrous. Head strongly inclined from longitudinal body axis, about as wide as mesoscutum. Vertex (
Fig. 21
) finely sculptured with microscopic setae and scaly micro structures that are relatively large, smooth and dense. Genal processes (
Fig. 20
) cone-shaped, moderately divergent and subacute apically, about as long as vertex along median suture, covered with long setae. Antenna slender and relatively short; terminal setae (
Fig. 26
) of different lengths, longer one about 1.5 times as long as shorter one, and slightly shorter than antennal segment X. Metatibia with blunt basal spine, apical spurs arranged as 1 + 3 + 1 . Fore wing (
Fig. 28
) oval, widest in the middle; pterostigma relatively long, ending in the apical 2 / 5 of cell r 1 ; cell cu 1 near quadrate, curvature of vein Cu 1 a relatively strong; surface spinules present in all cells, leaving wide spinule-free stripes along veins, fields narrowing along wing margin in cells r 1 , r 2 , m 1 , m 2 and cu 1 .

Male terminalia: Proctiger (

Fig. 
22

) slender and slightly curved, covered with sparse short setae. Paramere (
Figs 22, 24
) lamellar and slender; apex tooth-shaped, slightly projected cephalad; setae present in both inner and outer surface, particularly dense and long in basal half of inner surface, and along anterior and posterior margin; uneven on outer surface, more densely spaced in posterior half. Apical dilatation (

Fig. 
23

) of aedeagus spoonshaped, with rounded tip; sclerotised end tube of ductus ejaculatorius near straight. Subgenital plate (

Fig. 
22

) with several setae that vary in length along dorsal margin, ventral surface evenly covered with short setae.

