subSubSection.paragraph:
Female terminalia (
Fig. 25
): Proctiger weakly concave dorsally, covered with setae that vary in length; laterally and apex of apical part sparsely covered with peg setae that are relatively long, gradually replaced by normal setae basally. Anus large, nearly half as long as the proctiger longitudinally. Subgenital plate covered with short setae on ventral surface, with several peg setae at subapex.

Winter form: Differing from summer form in: Body much larger than summer form. Terminal setae (
Fig. 27
) of antenna short, the longer one about 1.5 times long as the shorter one, about half long as antennal segment X. Fore wing (
Fig. 29
) oblong oval, widest at apical third; 4 obscure radular areas present in cells cu 1 , m 2 , m 1 and r 2 (the one in r 2 smaller and variable in size among individuals), surface spinules reduced to small area along claval suture.

Structures: Body oblong oval. Dorsal surface (
Fig. 30
) unevenly covered with capitate setae that vary in length. Ventral surface of abdomen (
Fig. 30
) covered with simple setae that are longer laterally. Micro spinules present on both dorsal and ventral surfaces as shown in
Fig. 30
; on dorsal surface short, lamellar and multicuspid; on ventral surface long, spinous and unicuspid. Ocular seta (
Fig. 30
) capitate and relatively long. A long capitate seta (
Fig. 30
) present behind compound eye near body margin on dorsal surface. Antenna (
Fig. 30
) slender, 7 -segmented, apices of segments 3 and 5 each with a rhinarium, two rhinaria on segment 7 . Four pairs of capitate setae present on head anterior margin and submargin (
Fig. 30
). A sclerite with a spiracle present on ventral surface between praecoxa and mesocoxa, and a sclerite with a spiracle present on ventral surface between mesocoxa and metacoxa (
Fig. 30
). Fore wing pad with a row of 9–11 capitate setae that vary in length along outer margin, hind wing pad with two capitate setae at distal angle (
Fig. 30
). Dorsal surface of mesotibia with 2 long capitate setae; dorsal surface of metatibia with 1 long and 1 short capitate setae (
Fig. 30
). Tarsal arolium (
Fig. 32
) petiolate and fanshaped, relatively wide apically. 2 + 2 lateral free sclerites (
Fig. 30
) bearing a spiracle each present on ventral surface of abdomen. Caudal plate (
Fig. 31
) relatively large, with a pair of spiracle on either side of circum-anal ring. Outer circum-anal ring (
Fig. 31
) oval, with anterior margin strongly concave, posterior margin almost straight and lateral margins convex. Inner circum-anal ring (
Fig. 31
) more or less subparallel to outer, with lateral margins more evenly curved. Ventral surface of caudal plate (
Fig. 31
) with 2 + 2 simple setae right anterior to outer circumanal ring, 2 simple setae within the suture, a hemicycle row of simple setae from around the spiracles to anterior of anal suture, a series of simple setae near anterior margin and a series of simple setae near posterior margin. Abdominal margin (
Fig. 30
) bearing 7 pairs of long and 3 pairs of short capitate setae, lacking sectasetae.
